It serves as the parent company for Google and various subsidiaries (e.g., Google Fiber, Waymo, Verily, Wing, Isomorphic Labs), granting greater autonomy to group companies operating beyond core internet services.

Traded on Nasdaq (Class A shares), part of S&P 100, S&P 500, Nasdaq-100. Issued debt; invests in companies like Uber, United Masters, Medium.
- **Operations & Legal**: Regulated in regions like US, Japan, France; faced lawsuits (e.g., sued Uber, labor violations), settlements (e.g., 0.7% of yearly earnings in 2020), NLRB cases, mass layoffs (12,000 jobs, ~6%). Expanded worldwide; filed bankruptcy-related in Russia.
- **Other**: Launched Google Code of Conduct; granted patents (e.g., to Uber); economic activity tracked by sources like Yahoo Finance, Reuters, SEC filings.

Investor relations: alphabet.com, abc.xyz. For detailed filings, see Alphabet Inc. 2021/2023/2024 Annual Form 10-K Reports.

results.question: Who are the founders of Google (and later Alphabet)?
results.agent_answer:
**Larry Page and Sergey Brin are the founders of Google (and later Alphabet).**

They co-founded Google in 1998 while PhD students at Stanford University. In 2015, they restructured Google under a new parent company, **Alphabet Inc.**, which they established and led—Page as CEO (until 2019) and Brin as president (until 2019).
